Apollon is an educational modeling tool used by students and instructors to create, share, and assess UML diagrams. Its reusable editor supports standalone, mobile, and Artemis-based workflows, creating a need for consistent and accessible modeling across devices and teaching scenarios.

Before this thesis, several interactions required unnecessary manual effort, collaborators had limited awareness of each other's activity, and important workflows differed between applications. The coexistence of a legacy editor and a reengineered Apollon version also complicated maintenance and integration. These limitations affected diagram editing, collaborative and mobile use, educational integration, and export.

This thesis improves the usability and integration of Apollon through an iterative development process. The work simplifies diagram editing, introduces collaboration awareness, strengthens diagram management and mobile workflows, and makes visual exports more reliable. It also integrates the maintained Apollon version into Artemis while preserving quiz and assessment workflows. As a focused compatibility result of this migration, Athena's parser and playground support the earlier and current serialized model formats required by the relevant feedback workflows. The resulting work provides a more consistent foundation for modeling across individual study, teamwork, teaching, and assessment contexts.
